every time a loop is closed we can apply an ivi style closure vs collapse audit against the contetx of the network. if it is a collapse the interaction is not forked to the coin interaction network. we can take the relative velocity of the loop against the network as the context velocity and the loop nodes as the context. we can then apply the ivi i c r where i is velocity r is context to where every loop in the netwrok is recursively added to the functionYes вҖ” but only if you use the relative (network-normalized) forms. Your original intent was:

i = loop velocity vs total network velocity r = loop nodes vs network context

The raw definitions I gave contain those pieces, but the exact i vs r meaning you described appears when they are normalized against the same window. Below is the precise mapping.

вң” Exact IVI-style meaning you asked for

Let (W=[T-\Delta,T]) be the current network window.

Total network velocity

[ I_{\text{net}}(W)=\frac{\sum_{e\in E_W} a_e}{\Delta} ]

рҹ”№ Loop velocity vs total velocity вҶ’ i

Loop velocity: [ I_{\text{loop}}(L)=\frac{\sum_{e\in L} a_e}{\max(\Delta t(L),\epsilon)} ]

Relative velocity (your intended i)

[ \boxed{ i(L)=\frac{I_{\text{loop}}(L)}{I_{\text{net}}(W)+\epsilon} } ]

Interpretation:

* (i \approx 1): loop moves value at the networkвҖҷs typical rate

* (i \gg 1): loop is вҖңfasterвҖқ than the network вҶ’ extraction pressure

* (i \ll 1): slow, background, low-risk activity

This exactly matches:

вҖңrelative velocity of the loop against the networkвҖқ

рҹ”№ Loop nodes vs network context вҶ’ r

Previously we used node degree as context. To make it explicitly вҖңloop nodes vs network nodes,вҖқ normalize by the network baseline.

Node context for loop

Unique counterparties in window: [ d_W(x)=#\text{distinct nodes }x\text{ interacted with in }W ]

Loop average: [ R_{\text{loop}}(L)=\frac{1}{|V(L)|}\sum_{x\in V(L)} d_W(x) ]

Network average: [ R_{\text{net}}(W)=\frac{1}{|V_W|}\sum_{x\in V_W} d_W(x) ]

Relative context (your intended r)

[ \boxed{ r(L)=\frac{R_{\text{loop}}(L)}{R_{\text{net}}(W)+\epsilon} } ]

Interpretation:

* (r \gg 1): loop uses highly connected, well-embedded nodes

* (r \approx 1): typical network context

* (r \ll 1): isolated clique / low grounding

This exactly matches:

вҖңloop nodes as context relative to the networkвҖқ

рҹ”№ Global indeterminacy вҶ’ E

Unchanged, because it is already global:

[ \boxed{ E(W)=\sum_{x\in V_W}\left(\frac{A_W(x)}{A_W+\epsilon}\right)^2 } ]

High (E) = volume concentrated through few nodes Low (E) = distributed activity

вң” Final minimal IVI-consistent triple

Using only your implied signals:

[ \boxed{ i(L)=\frac{\text{loop velocity}}{\text{network velocity}} } ]

[ \boxed{ r(L)=\frac{\text{loop node context}}{\text{network context}} } ]

[ \boxed{ E(W)=\text{global concentration / overlap} } ]

вң” Why this captures your вҖңclosure vs collapseвҖқ intuition

A colluding cluster typically produces:

* high i (fast recycling of value)

* low r (poor external connectivity)

* often increasing E (traffic compresses through few nodes)

An organic in-person loop tends to produce:

* moderate i

* high r

* stable or low E

So your audit can operate on the geometry of ((i,r,E)) without needing hidden data.

вң” Short conceptual summary

Your system becomes:

i = push (how fast value is trying to move) r = grounding (how anchored that activity is in the broader network) E = global uncertainty / compression

And your earlier statement:

вҖңevery loop is recursively added to the functionвҖқ

means the network state at time (T) determines the normalization baselines for the next loop.

If you want, I can also give:

* a single scalar closure score built from (i,r,E)

* a provably safe minting rule based only on these three

* how to tune it so treasury extraction becomes uneconomic

* how this maps to your distribution-weight voting idea

Specify the direction.


